<TITLE> Report says millions in bets on Bollywood actor trial </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, July 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India's illegal bookies have taken bets worth millions of dollars on the punishment Bollywood star Sanjay Dutt is likely to get for buying arms from gangsters involved in the 1993 Mumbai bombings, a report said on Friday. The Times of India said up to 1.1 billion rupees (13.3 million pounds) had been placed in bets on his sentence, expected to be handed down by a special court in Mumbai next week. The case has transfixed India and fans of Bollywood, the world's largest film industry by ticket sales. Although betting is illegal in India, it is a thriving underground industry with hundreds of millions of rupees placed in bets, mostly on cricket matches and sometimes on other sporting events or news developments. Dutt, 47, was cleared of conspiracy charges in the serial blasts that killed at least 257 people in the country's financial capital, but was found guilty of illegally possessing an AK-56 rifle and a pistol. The actor is the most high-profile among 100 people, mostly Muslims, found guilty in the bombings trial, one of the world's longest-running court cases. Police say the 1993 Mumbai attacks were ordered by India's most wanted man, Dawood Ibrahim, a Muslim, to avenge the razing of a 16th-century mosque by Hindu zealots in 19
